## Why user-downloadable projects can look ‚Äúmagra‚Äù even when your system ‚Äúworks‚Äù

There are two separate ‚Äúthinness‚Äù failure modes that are easy to confuse:

### Downloads are exporting the preview artifact or partial file set instead of a runnable project

The system prompt is designed around an assumption: there are ‚ÄúExisting Files‚Äù in the runtime base, and the model should not regenerate them unless needed. That means the model might output only a subset of files, relying on the base scaffold/runtime to provide the rest. ÓàÄfileciteÓàÇturn13file0ÓàÇL1-L1ÓàÅ

Bra Branch finalization explicitly merges generated output with scaffold base files when a scaffold is present (`mergeGeneratedProjectFiles()`), producing a ‚Äúcomplete‚Äù file set for the version. ÓàÄfileciteÓàÇturn16file0ÓàÇL1-L1ÓàÅ
That merge happens during finalization. ÓàÄfileciteÓàÇturn15file0ÓàÇL1-L1ÓàÅ

If your ‚Äúdownload user project‚Äù code path is exporting **pre-merge** files (or exporting the preview‚Äôs inferred ‚Äúrenderable subset‚Äù), users may receive something that looks skeletal.

### You are expecting `vercel-scrape` (external templates) to be the ‚Äústuff users download‚Äù

Bra Branch is pretty explicit that external Vercel templates are **reference material** and that only the internal scaffold set is used as a runtime base. ÓàÄfileciteÓàÇturn20file0ÓàÇL1-L1ÓàÅ

So if some part of your system started treating `vercel-scrape` entries as ‚Äúdownloadable projects,‚Äù you‚Äôll get ‚Äúmagra‚Äù results because ingestion outputs are not meant to be standalone apps.

